The definition, typology, research of bilingualism. The development of a bilingual child. Interference. Estonian-Russian bilingualism. The critical analysis of the legislation and  educational possibilities of minority-children. Bilingualism and special education.Compiling individual education plans for minority-children.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to give theoretical knowledge of the development of bilingual children with the emphasis on speech development/second language acquisition. To give an overview of currently available educational options for minority-children and to teach students  to identify and analyse the possible problems in development and education of minority-children..Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student knows in what way the speech production and comprehension as well as speech development of monolingual children and bilingual children differ; differs the mistakes in language use  due to the influence of the second language and due to speech and language disorder; chooses appropriate methods and materials for supporting second language acquisition; develops a supportive attitude towards multilingualism and multiculturalism in the Estonian educational system.
